Literals in Java

 Definition
- A literal is a fixed value that you write directly in your code.
- It represents the actual data that gets stored in a variable.
- Unlike variables (which are named storage), literals are the raw values themselves.
 Example:
int age = 25;        // here 25 is a literal
char grade = 'A';    // 'A' is a literal
boolean isActive = true; // true is a literal

 Analogy
Think of literals as the items you put inside lockers (variables):
- The locker (variable) has a name and type.
- The item (literal) is the actual value you place inside.
- Example: Locker named age → item placed inside = 25.

Literals in Java
│
├── Integer Literals
│   ├── Decimal (100)
│   ├── Octal (010)
│   ├── Hexadecimal (0x1A)
│   └── Binary (0b1010)
│
├── Floating-Point Literals
│   ├── double (3.14)
│   └── float (2.5f)
│
├── Character Literals ('A', '\n')
├── String Literals ("Hello")
├── Boolean Literals (true, false)
└── Null Literal (null)